http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Class Guitar Curriculum Standards for grades 9-12.
Singing - Students will sing, alone and with others, a varied repertoire of music.
Demonstrate an understanding of basic elements of vocal technique by singing major/minor scales and familiar songs (e.g., folk tunes)
Employ basic vocal technique and aural skills to sing familiar songs with simple guitar accompaniment patterns
Performing - Students will perform on instruments, alone and with others, a varied repertoire of music.
Demonstrate proper guitar technique: posture, hand position, and appropriate fingering choices.
Perform with expression and technical accuracy a large and varied repertoire of guitar literature with some pieces memorized.
Demonstrate well-developed ensemble skills through performance in large and small ensembles.
Improvising - Students will improvise melodies, variations, and accompaniments.
Improvise simple melodies over a given chord progression.
Improvise rhythmic or melodic variations on a given melody.
Improvise simple chord accompaniments for given melodies.
Composing - Students will compose and arrange music within specified guidelines.
Compose guitar music within specified guidelines, using technology when available.
Arrange and transpose various guitar pieces within specified guidelines, using technology when available.
Reading and Notating - Students will read and notate music.
Demonstrate the ability to read and notate music by identifying and defining standard notational symbols.
Accurately sight-read select guitar music at various levels of difficulty.
Listening and Analyzing - Students will listen to, analyze, and describe music.
Listen to and analyze a varied repertoire of Renaissance, Baroque, Classical, and Contemporary guitar music, describing the specific musical characteristics of each period and genre.

Listen to and analyze the uses of musical elements in a varied repertoire of exemplary works from each musical period, identifying and describing what makes the works unique, interesting, and expressive.
Evaluating - Students will evaluate music and music performances.
Develop and apply specific criteria related to accuracy, technical difficulty, and interpretation to critically evaluate compositions, arrangements, performances of others, and personal performances.
Evaluate guitar performances (of others and personal) in terms of aesthetic quality and explain the musical elements used to evoke feelings and emotions.
Interdisciplinary Connections - Students will understand relationships between music, the other arts, and disciplines outside the arts.
Compare and contrast how guitar music relates to other disciplines within the arts.
Evaluate how guitar music and other disciplines outside of the arts are related.
Historical and Cultural Relationships - Students will understand music in relation to history and culture.
Evaluate examples of guitar music by genre, historical period, and culture.
Compare and contrast genres of guitar music, and the guitarist and composers associated with each genre, within specified historical periods and cultures.
